The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 29, 2004 				 Grasim fourth-quarter net leaps
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								Mumbai, April 28: Grasim Industries Ltd has reported a roaring performance for the fourth quarter ended March 31, 2004. Net profit rose to Rs 282.07 crore against Rs 49 lakh posted in the corresponding previous quarter.																								In the fourth quarter of 2002-03, Grasim had suffered a loss of Rs 208.62 crore on the sale of trade investments which had an impact on its bottomline.																								Total income during the period under review was up at Rs 1,625.27 crore compared with Rs 1,274.91 crore a year earlier. 																								The board has recommended a dividend of Rs 14 per share for 2003-04 and total payout towards dividend is Rs 144.8 crore. 																								Grasim posted a higher net profit for fiscal 2003-04 at Rs 779.26 crore against Rs 367.58 crore in the previous fiscal. Total income was up at Rs 5,413.61 crore compared with Rs 4,739.18 crore in 2002-03.																								Talking to newspersons, D. D. Rathi, chief financial officer, said that the company has targeted a capex programme of Rs 534 crore for the next two years. Of this, Rs 410 crore will be allocated this year. 																								The company will infuse Rs 177 crore into its cements business, a capex of Rs 272 crore has been earmarked for viscose staple fibre (VSF), Rs 35 crore for chemicals and Rs 50 crore for its other businesses.																								Grasim is planning to expand its VSF segment through de-bottlenecking and setting up of a development centre. 																								Apart from this, it is also planning to modernise the cement unit and hike cement capacity by one million tonnes to 14.4 million tonnes over the next 12-15 months.																								Grasim revealed that during the year, realisations from its VSF business improved by 6 per cent. It is now developing new applications and superior quality VSF.																								Its cement business registered a 7 per cent growth vis a vis the industry growth of 5 per cent. To leverage on its brand equity, Birla Plus, Birla Super and Birla Ready Mix have been identified as national brands. Regional brands will be gradually phased out.																								The company will shortly make an open offer for the controlling stake in Larsen amp; Toubros demerged cement business, officials revealed. Rathi, however, maintained that Grasim is not planning to revise upwards its open offer price. 																								He added that Grasim will shortly announce its plans for amp;Ts cement brands.
